reviewText: I was in the audience at Unity in Ashland, Oregon when James Twyman announced he was making this movie to honor "Golden Indigo's". I kept up with the production in the Ashland newspaper and then I got to see it in the spring at the Ashland Film Festival. Number 1 I love Shirley Knight in it and Tom Skerrit has always been a favorite since the TV show Picket Fences. The scenery of the Redwood Highway is really the Oregon/California Redwood Highway it's lovely and so are the coast scenes. It's a sweet story, an almost possible story, not sure I could walk 80 miles in a few days but the people and relationships are authentic. I got to see the movie a second time in Santa Fe and it seemed better then the first time even. Love the scenes best with Shirley and Tom. As I approach 65 I realize we are never 'old' inside, we are still an ageless spirit full of life and vitality that's what this story is about.
People do a lot of things for a lot of reasons, but how often do you see someone putting down their pride and doing something for the sake of love?

This is one of the best movies I have seen in a long time and I am not even part of the target audience (baby boomer, I am a Generation X person looking for good films).  I highly recommend this movie.  Lets put this way my family even took a trip to the Redwood Highway just to see the areas that are featured in the film.

Shirley Knight is SUCH a natural in the role of Marie, an older person who has been lately ignored by her family and decides to journey out alone, on foot, on a long journey to find her "roots." It's always a pleasure to see veteran actor Tom Skerritt, too, as one of the people she meets, who decides to befriend her.

No spoilers, here, except to let you know that there IS a happy ending! A great film for the entire family.

I really enjoyed this video and Shirley Knight was great in her performance as Ann Marie.  The story is about an older person traveling not only down a physical highway but her walking trip was also a journey into self discovery as well as facing some of her own demons as well as her past.  Tom Skirrit was excellent in his support role.  While I though the other actors portraying her family were a bit stiff and stilted, the people she met were the most real.  I could identify with the main character because her spunk and determination and stubbornness that could get her into trouble reminded me of something my own mom would have done.  I could identify with the family worry but see how the older woman needed to do this walk down Redwood Highway for her own sale.  Excellent video, little profanity, some adult situations and enjoyable!

Shirley Knight-bless her heart IMHO has never gotten  the recognition she deserves as an actress. I believe she was in her late 70's when this fine movie was filmed- and she displays the energy and stamina that would put to shame most folks 1/3 of her age.  This movie is a delight and I recommend it to all. It has the qualities that matter to me in a superior film- that I are hard to find in todays films. First-it is not too long nor too short. Second, it has characters that the viewer will care about. Third it has magnificent scenery, photographed from Shirley Knight's perspective-that is of a walker or hiker- which is a more thoughtful and reflective and meaningful perspective that that of most of us in our chaotic and busy world of work and automobile travel.  Fourth it shows a profound truth about America's "ordinary people"-workaday folks- that I have heard from many people who have immigrated to America and have lived in several developed and developing countries- that Americans on the whole are overwhelmingly "GOOD" people- and this is NOT universally true across the globe. Fifth like the excellent movie "Suffragettes" with Helena  Bonham Carter-is shows a subtle sophisticated modern and discerning feminism throughout-in the interactions conversations non verbal communications woman -woman and man-woman that are a joy to watch. Sixth  I think whomever directed this movie did a superb job- as like all good movies-there was zero "waste" in this movie-every prop scene word in the movie (like a superior theatre production() moved the plot along or unfolded a nuance of the character that deepened our look into their world-what that means to the character-those they interact with and what it means to us.
  Seventh- there is a discerning optimism and hope about life in this movie. The characters all grow and change in the movie. The conversations of the characters ring true. When it rains in Oregon (there the movie was filmed) you hear the rain gently falling on the soft earth in a rural area and you can almost smell as well as see the freshness of the soft earth.
  Eighth  Tom Skeritt is a good actor- or to me at least a "re actor"-in a strange way like a more famous and very different personality of a much earlier film era- John Wayne who "re acted" to others in the cast with his dialog and remarks. Skeritt and Knight's character's  chemistry  is  palpable and a delight to watch.  Skeritt played a pivotal role in this film as intentionally or not mentoring Knight in a gentle and profound sense in her movement to get in touch with herself and come to terms with what she wants from life at this stage in her life.

This was a feel good movie that was a light and easy way to spend an evening. The story was uplifting to see all the good people she meets along the way- and it was great the way she dealt the the scary meth head druggie guy that was trying to rob her!  I can see the allure of a long walk to help you think about life, especially since Marie's has changed so much in recent years with her being moved from her hometown to the retirement community (which most of us would happily move into with the pool, breakfast buffet, fireplaces in the rooms, and hot tub!)  Overall, it was a nice movie that was clean and entertaining.  While it would be safe for the whole family, I think the movie is more aimed toward adults, as some of the issues are deep and I am not sure a child would really understand.  The movie also had a lot of beautiful scenery of Oregon, so that's a plus as well.

A light-hearted film with subtle humor, and a good storyline with a happy ending. Real and more true to life  different from mainstream movie hits. I enjoyed the themes of an older woman empowering herself, and that life-affirming, soul-fulfilling journeys are never out of reach. I also enjoyed the gentle story-telling of how the paramount individual freewill that each of us needs and seeks can get trampled in the culturally accepted and well-intentioned yet often misguided attempts to be responsible and care for others, especially loved ones.

I've been a fan of Shirley Knight's for many years, since I first saw her as a shy but luminous teenager in The Dark at the Top of the Stairs, and later in The Outer Limits and the wonderful film Mary and Tim.  I liked Redwood Highway a lot for several reasons: 1) Marie is a PERSON, not some caricature of an old person,  2) what happens is believable, quite realistic, and  3) it's a revealing character study.  It also has a spiritual/supernatural twist that appealed very much to me.  We're on a quest along with stubborn Marie, a woman who perhaps foolishly refuses to be constrained by age and circumstance.  She meets some interesting people along the way.  And, she learns a thing or two- growth/change is possible, at any age.  Great, satisfying ending.

Nice character study of a woman newly widowed, newly retired in a retirement community within 4 hours of her son.  I had some problems with it.
First, the son moves her, WITHOUT HER CAR!, to a town closer to him but 4 hours away from him.
Why not put her in the SAME TOWN as he lives if he is going to make sure she doesn't have a car?
She does not have sight or hearing or thinking problems.  It is about her 3 day walk on Redwood Highway to her granddaughter's wedding.  So 4 hours x 65 car miles is 260 miles that theoretically she walks (with a few car rides here and there).  She is in GREAT SHAPE!  She has sweet little adventures with helpful people (and one scary guy) on the road.  She has an issue from her pass that haunts her.  She is a very good camper and walker.
I am approaching retirement so I was interested in seeing movie versions of how people do this.  The son seems to have moved her away from her little town of Bend, Oregon right after her husband dies and now she doesn't have a support system because he is still 4 HOURS AWAY!
But she is so independent, I can't see her agreeing to the move unless she was so done under by her husband's death, but it seems her son would have been more sensitive to that and let her wait to make a decision since it is common knowledge that you shouldn't make any major decisions until at least 6 months after a major death in your life.  So 3 stars but lots of plot problems.  Nice acting, though.

Leaving aside the laughable absurdity that an old woman who could walk 60 miles in 3 days by herself carrying a large backpack would almost certainly never be in an old-age home in the first place, this entire film is just sentimental mush full of stereotypical new-age feel-good nonsense. Aside from the beautiful scenery, excellent cinematography and Tom Skerrit's performance in a small role, the overall quality of this film is barely above that of a glorified TV-movie-of-the-week, but aimed at cheaply manipulating the emotions of an older audience.  There are many films of this kind that earn the emotions of their audience genuinely and truthfully: Ikiru, Atlantic City, Umberto D., Tokyo Story and A Trip to Bountiful.  Watch those if you want to see a film about aging done right.

Unfortunately, the plot has major holes in it, the casting was way off, and the main character is basically impossible to feel any sympathy or connection to. Watch this movie if you want to get a feel for this corner of Northern California/Southern Oregon, but be prepared to be exasperated.

Although I enjoyed the movie, I didn't find it particularly convincing. Maybe it's because I had to be responsible for my mom when we had to move her 600 miles from her home to an assisted living facility and then be responsible for her welfare for 2.5 years. I also am not a Shirley Knight fan. Anyway, the gist of the movie is people who are caustic and intractable create huge gulfs for their family members to cross and get tired of trying. Then when the family backs away, they feel sorry for themselves. I can see her walking 80 miles just to prove a point that she is still capable and independent, but I can also she that if she got hurt or killed, she wouldn't mind at all if the family felt guilty. I just found the ending implausible because people who live 70 years with such abrasive personalities do not suddenly see the error of their ways and apologize for their harsh comments and behavior and then live happily ever after.

Good story of an elderly, independent and spunky woman whose over protective son has put put in an assisted living home. The son insists she is too frail to do much and apparently instruct the staff to impose a strict limitation on almost all activity, even forbidding her to walk around the grounds on her own. She evades these restraints at every opportunity, ultimately escaping and embarking on a long walk on the highway. Turns out well in the end, but an odd conclusion with too many loose ends to be ultimately satisfying.

I thought this movie, while interesting in premise and subject material, was not done well enough to be really worth the time. I'm sure the plot is meant to be uplifting as Shirley Knight's character perseveres doggedly in her determined effort to make the trek to her granddaughter's coastal wedding all on her own. The plot is predictable and there is no real reason for the viewer to connect with the woman, unless perhaps admiration for her grit through all her trials and tribulations. Not enough was explained to create real sympathy for her character, because even as she comes to change her mind about judging her granddaughter, her behavior is thoughtless as to the tension she is creating for her family.  As to Tom Skerritt staring in the movie, he really was only in a small portion of the action.  Much more could have been developed with his character's interaction with Knight's.  It's just not a movie I'd want to see again.

Plot lines of her unhappiness at the facility and conflict with the granddaughter over her choice of mates notwithstanding, the idea of her throwing food from the buffet table into her pack and taking off on foot was both exhilarating and a little terrifying. A woman in an assisted living center likes taking very long walks. After a terrible argument with her son and granddaughter, over her granddaughter's decision to marry young, the old gal finds herself estranged. She swears that she will take revenge on her daughter by refusing to attend the wedding. She regrets the ultimatum and, in an impulsive move, she loads up a backpack and begins a long walk to the wedding. its a couple days' worth of walking and she is never far from her own first love. Like an odyssey, each experience she has enlightens her, and the viewer. To understand that junction between the fear that one's own experience will be repeated, and the hope that one's granddaughter will enjoy the happiness in an early marriage that her grandmother was denied, that is the internal walk this old woman takes. Plus she spends the night in a tree house with Tom Skerritt. Lovely scenery, a simple story, and a nice way to spend 90 minutes.

And I'm not even mentioning Tom Skerrit's character who, from their brief contact, truly had an interest in her, but was simply another road to nowhere. It's not that I want every film to wrap everything up with a big red bow; I don't! But I do like to feel that there was a point to be made (sorry, none noted). Still, worth watching for the gorgeous Oregon scenery and truly fine acting by all involved.

OMgoodness, a film about a favorite place of mine, the Redwoods. I am watching a film (one of my favorite things to do) and Shirley Knight is delightful as a retired red-head in this low budget sleeper that is worth AT LEAST 2 hours of your time. She meets a handsome widower, some oriented hikers, a bartender-nurse as she seeks the fellowship of her granddaughter's wedding. I'm not sure about you, but to me, this is a coming of age flick. I've traveled the Redwood Highway myself in the past few years. So Shirley as Marie walks the Redwood Highway because her son took her car from her. Her legs and per pride are the only things left perhaps, but Marie proves to have formitable legs as she dances into your heart in this favorite movie. The Redwood part of my motivation to move up here to the Pacific NW and this movie highlights some favorite scenes from this area of the US. If you haven't flown into Sacramento, driven to Northern California along the coast to the Redwoods, it's time to go.... Marie moves pillows at stops along the way like she's home, because Marie IS home inside her skin. Marie is not "nuts" in my book, son , but I'm thinking about an homage to Knight for giving me permission to be weird in yet another way. REI, here I come.

I saw TWO phenomenal movies today on Prime (love my Prime membership)! This was one of them. Shirley Knight is a phenomenal actress, and she's better with age. The storyline is beautifully done. And the surprise bit by Tom Skerritt is a delight. Highly recommended.

I live in Brookings, OR (approximately 5 miles north of the California/Oregon border on the Pacific coastline), and I watched this movie for the scenery, to see how much of it I would recognize.  There was a lot of scenery I recognized, but since I know the area, I also know that some of the scenes were preposterous.  Like when she drops out of the Redwood Forest (which is in California, by the way), and suddenly she is on North Harris Beach, which is on the north side of Brookings, and 30 miles north of the Redwood Forest and the Redwood Highway, walking south from an area on the beach that has no access but from the direction in which she is going.  The Redwood Highway is known to us locals as "199", and it mostly runs through the northern part of California, with just a little bit in Oregon.  We never call it the more romantic name of Redwood Highway, because we all hate it, due to the hairpin curves it is comprised of, and because if we want to head to civilization, we have to take 199 for 2 hours (in a car, not on foot!) to get there.  There are some beautiful places along 199, especially in the few miles there are that go through the Redwoods, but it is mostly just curve after curve after curve.  It was fun to see many places in this movie that I know and live around, but I thought the story line was pretty lame.  If I didn't want to see the scenery in the movie, I would have quit watching about half way through it.

If potlucks are your thing, this is a hearty tuna-noodle casserole. This is a great film to watch with your Granny or Grampy.  The best part was when she fought off the bad guys with "Bear Away."  The climax of the film was the dramatic lead-up to a steamy romance between Granny and a young, super-gorgeous woman she met on the road (after Granny bashed her head on a rock while casting a fishing line into the river)...afterwards when she was ambling along the highway, she got picked up by the great looking babe , who then took back to her barThey really got us on that one, because after all the lead up, nothing happened. The romance just fizzled out when the booze wore off. But we should've seen that one coming after the almost triste between Granny and the elderly Burl carver at the beginning of her adventure.

She did manage to make it to her granddaughter's wedding (to a personalty-less drummer).

We were left wondering who had to foot the bill for the massive police Granny Hunt. Those cops sure were determined, but Granny stayed ahead of them all along the way of her back-packing, foot blistering journey. We had wondered if this film might have a hidden and subversive message about police work -- C'mon, a state-wide wo-man hunt eluded them day after day--  even though she was wearing a huge backpack while walking in broad daylight down the only highway to the coast. Hmmmmm. Sounds Fishy. What do you think?  After all was said and done, it's a real heart-warmer not to be missed.

I'll be the odd rating since I thought Marie's son and even her granddaughter were selfish. The son sticks his mother, played by Shirley Knight, in a nursing home, probably for some of the same reasons it's done every day. Marie's granddaughter is irritated because her grandmother, who is a bit more experienced and wiser in life than she is, disapproves of her marrying an older man. (A musician who plays drums and he didn't appear very successful). The granddaughter phones her grandmother and tells her she can live without her and she's marrying the guy anyway. I would never have said such a thing to either of my grandparents.
To prove she's capable and still has her facilities and strength, Marie walks 80 miles to the wedding with a lot of diversions along the way. Here you have a son and his daughter who stand there on the beach, all dressed up for the wedding while Marie is still missing. The granddaughter is going to go ahead with the ceremony anyway with high approval from her dad. How's that for selfish when the search should have continued for Marie.
Shirley Knight is a great actress in this film and the character of Marie is smarter and stronger than her son and granddaughter. I doubt very seriously the son and granddaughter could have hiked 80 miles alone.

I totally enjoyed watching Redwood Highway.  I marvelled at the strength and independence of the main character.  She was stubborn and opinionated and harbored a lot of anger towards her son - mainly for feeling like he gave her no choice or input of where she would live - and towards her earlier self as a young girl, not following her heart to be with her one true love.  When she decided to journey the 80 miles to her Grandaughter's wedding, she packed and planned with good planning and thought.  The anger slowly softened and 'settled' as each mile came and went.  She met some good, honest people as well as a few lowlifes along the way.  All of which seemed to teach her acceptance of how and what her life had become.  I won't spoil it for you as far as how far she went and what ultimately happened - you just need to watch it!  The scenery is beautiful - I'll bet you'll want to "walk in her shoes" after you see this!

Ann Marie, who says she goes by "Marie" (Shirley Knight), decides to take her own "Sentimental Journey" on home - carrying memories of her marriage and former life.  A trek of 80 miles on foot to reach Brookings, Oregon to make amends with her granddaughter, Naomi (Zena Grey).  Upon learning of her wedding to a man who is twelve years older than she, Marie just did not agree and felt the marriage would be a huge mistake.  Problem is, Marie does not mince words and is quite perturbed with the situation, although, she has a much bigger issue with her son, Michael (James LeGros).  Needless to say, they have not had a tight relationship, mainly tumult since her husband passed away when Michael was quite young.

He has coerced her to move into a retirement home far from the town she loved so much and speaks of always, Bend Oregon.  He wants her closer to him without having to drive about four hours to visit, which he did prior to moving her.  Marie calls this a straight up nursing home and is not happy, not in the slightest.  I won't mince words here either; Marie hates it and why wouldn't she?  The loss of one's autonomy through your own ability to decide matters is almost a death punch.  I could understand both of their points of view.  Michael gets exasperated with her when she just takes off on her walks away from her 'home' during which she will walk for hours a day - sometimes to the point of people asking, "Where has Marie gone to now"?

Gary Lundgren directs a very spirited, and tenacious as a Jack Russell Terrier, Marie on a sojourn to see the Oregon coast of her past and to reach a touching destination.  This coastline has seduced her and never ceased in calling to her wanderlust to go back after 45 years.  The tall, and beckoning redwoods and pines that scrape the sky, insist that Marie packs up and leaves after a bitingly spiteful phone call from an afterwards fully remorseful Naomi; a bit too little and a bit too late.  What follows is the highlight of the film itself.

A cantankerous although sensitive Marie is slowly traveling along some of the most magnificent scenery of our own gorgeous country (Fabulous cinematography by Patrick Neary). I loved following each of her footsteps along with her, marveling over how she does it and how she views things in her life.  Marie meets some people along the way, one is a wonderfully friendly and flirty, Pete Peterson (Tom Skerritt).  Who only wants to aid her along in her journey?  You decide.  She sleeps in the woods, makes her own fires, does a little fishing, cooks her own food and vanquishes help as much as she can.  Meeting a particularly sweet and lovely young woman, Stacia (Michelle Lombardo), from an occurrence on the trip allows Marie to finally let her hair down in a full-blown and fun Girls Night and a much needed indoor night of sleep, then up and onward again...

I fully enjoyed this journey on the "Redwood Highway" that Marie shares as I felt it was very personal.  The casting of the film is flawless as Shirley Knight does the ultimate portrayal of elder angst and rebellion tempered with a polite sweetness that spills out often.  A film that a family can enjoy together and one you will definitely appreciate if not for the scenery alone.  This is a brilliant trek that proves it is never too late to go back to your own roots.

Very nice film.  I normally do not purchase DVDs for movies however, I am an extra in this film and needed it (for bragging rights :) ). BUT I ended up really, really liking this movie... Great job Gary!

Wonderful movie!  Shirley Knight has you not only seeing but feeling her character's frustration struggling to maintain her independence in a new phase of her life. After losing what was home and life  to her, she is unhappy living in a comfortable "retirement" community.  She retaliates,reluctant to attend her grand daughter's wedding.  She rethinks and decides she is going to walk the beautifully scenic Redwood Highway to attend  the wedding after all  even though she isn't invited. Along the way she meets incredible people who participate in the journey as well as her own personal healing. She walks with sheer determination, devotion and spunk finding herself  healing old wounds and new ones along the way. She comes to realize something we all need to remember in our lives., That we are never too old to learn new things about life and about ourselves. Each time I watch it, I find treasures I missed.  The extraodinarysupporting cast including Tom Skerritt were priceless.

What vivacious retired woman wants to be placed in a retirement home, even though it seems to be a nice one. Marie, played by Shirley Knight goes out daily for long 4 hour walks. She is quite disturbed that her son talked her into moving to this retirement center from her beloved one in Bend, Oregon. But her son, Michael, played by James Le Gros, wanted her nearer to him. The four hour drive to Bend was too much. It seems Marie and Michael have always had somewhat of a contentious relationship. Marie's husband died early on in their marriage when Michael was small.

Marie's granddaughter is getting married to a man twelve years her senior, and Marie thinks she is making a mistake. Michael wants to drive her to the wedding, but Marie refuses half indignation and half stubbornness. Then she feels regret, and decides to strike out on her own to walk the 80 miles to Brookings, Oregon, on the ice an front. Of note this area has great memories for Marie at the beginning of her marriage. The film is essentially Marie's walk to Brookings, full of highlights and lowlights.

Shirley Knight gives us a bravura performance, a woman at retirement age who can walk 80 mikes is something most women her age would be very happy to do. Walking the last miles so to speak. Liked this film a great deal, and viewing the sights of Oregon from someone who has been there, is a lot of fun. The film has a gritty real feel to it. No fancy, dancy motels or posh meals, the fireside meals of apples, bananas, and muffins taken from the retirement center. A real walk in the woods. A film for the family, recognize your grandmother?

A walkabout movie that doesn't dwell in sentimentality. The protagonist, Marie, or Ann Marie Vaughn is a study in frustration --a senior citizen who no one listens to anymore. Moved into a retirement community against her will, the only way Marie can express her independence is by taking long walks everyday. Perhaps the daily journeys off the beaten path through town are a symbol of the restless spirit, not ready to have decisions made for her, even if they're made by family. She's no wimp --forthright and opinionated, Ann Marie is continuously annoyed.  After having a falling out with her granddaughter, Marie decides to walk 80 miles through the lushly forested Oregon Redwood Highway to make amends at granddaughter's wedding. Acted with a light touch, Shirley Knight  owns the role of Marie, and portrays a woman regaining her spirit on this long, and often difficult journey. Tom Skerrit gives a delightful turn as a local burl wood carver who aids her. The simple acts of caring mixed with playful flirtation is so lightly played, and one  hopes that Ann Marie will one day return to the charismatic Pete Peterson.
This isn't a film with drama just for the sake of it. Rather, it follows a character that most people would just as soon forget, instead watching her grow as she rediscovers her spirit within. In all of this, an Oscar nod for Shirley Knight.
Especially enjoyed the film as we are in a Retirement Community ourselves.  Great to see Shirley Knight in such a good role!

I grew up in Southern Oregon so, to be honest, I pre-ordered for the nostalgic value.  When I began hearing from friends who were lucky enough to still live there and see it in a movie theater, I knew the movie would be worthwhile....and it was more than that.  A sweet sensitive story of determination with a little orneriness that is so typical of my generation.  And Shirley Knight was wonderful at portraying it.  Tom Skerritt was an absolute natural displaying the genuineness of many men who live in the area where I grew up.  I will watch again and share it for memories and for lessons to learn.  No surprise ending, but a touching one just the same.

And yes - if you are going to be a purist - I have heard your complaint:  It is Coos Bay, not Brookings - so what I say!

A beautifully produced, filmed and enacted account of one woman's process of finding completion, healing of past memories and present relationships and personal triumph in her golden years. The film was so well paced that my interest was held every minute, and the scenery was absolutely breathtaking. Most of all I loved the Divine synchronicity of how Marie kept encountering loving, caring folks along the way who provided her with exactly what she most needed along her journey. It is just like that in life--we are never left alone--always along our Soul journey there will be angels in all types of guises looking out for our well being.  Well done James Twyman, cast and creative team.

I LOVE Tom Skerritt.  I wish he'd had a larger roll in the film.  The main character reminded me of my mother, a little lost with her roll in life now that she's older in age and her children have children of their own.  The protagonist doesn't just want to lay down and wait for death and she doesn't want people telling her how to live.  She's frustrated that people have placed restrictions on what she's capable of. She's got something to prove to others but more importantly to her self.  I think she needs to prove to herself more than anyone else that she can make the walk and I think she comes to terms with accepting help and admitting that she can't handle every situation alone.
